# 1st helper function

data_cleaning <- function(og_data, new_data, variables, names, values){
  
  # Select variables of interest + pivot longer
  
  new_data <- og_data |>
    select(country, {{ variables }}) |>
    pivot_longer(cols = {{ variables }},
                 names_to = {{ names }},
                 values_to = {{ values }})
  
  return(new_data)
  
}

# 2nd helper function

k_to_val <- function(data, variable){
  
  # Turn values of _k into integers
  
  data <- data |>
    mutate(across(.cols = {{ variable }},
                  .fns = ~ ifelse(str_detect(string = .x,
                                             pattern = "k|K"),
                                  1000*as.numeric(str_remove_all(string = .x,
                                                                 pattern = "k|K")),
                                  as.numeric(.x)
                                  )))
  
  return(data)
  
}

# Transform energy dataset into energy_long

energy_long <- data_cleaning(og_data = energy,
                             new_data = energy_long,
                             variables = `1975`:`2013`,
                             names = "year",
                             values = "energy_use")

# Transform _k values

energy_long <- k_to_val(data = energy_long,
                        variable = "energy_use")

# Transform gdp dataset into gdp_long

gdp_long <- data_cleaning(og_data = gdp,
                          new_data = gdp_long,
                          variables = `1975`:`2013`,
                          names = "year",
                          values = "gdp")

# Transform _k values

gdp_long <- k_to_val(data = gdp_long,
                          variable = "gdp")

# Join both datasets together

final_data <- inner_join(energy_long,
                         gdp_long, 
                         by = join_by(country, year))

Project Proposal

Gapminder: GDP Per Capita Vs. Energy Use Per Person

Gapminder is an independent Swedish foundation that collects reliable data on global topics in order to systematically combat âdevastating ignorance with a fact-based worldview everyone can understand.â They do this by combining data from multiple reliable sources in order to give the everyday person a more accurate view of what the world is like.

More information about Gapminder can be found here.

In particular, our group decided to investigate the relationship between GDP Per Capita, a measure of purchasing power, and Energy Use Per Person.

Data set #1: GDP Per Capita

The data set gdp_pcap.csv records the GDP per capita for various countries in a given year, or the value of everything produced in a country each year, divided by the countryâs population.This particular data sets records the GDP per capita of 195 countries in each year from 1800 to 2023, as well as the predicted GDP per capita in each year from 2024 until 2100. Gapminder labels the units of measurement for GDP per capita as constant PPP (Purchasing Power Parity) dollars. There are 195 rows in this data set, each one representing a different country, and 302 columns, each one representing a different year.

Data set #2: Energy Use per Person

The dataset energy_use_per_person.csv records the energy use per person in various countries, for each year from 1960 to 2013. In this case, energy use per person is referring to the use of primary energy before transformation to other end-use fuels. Gapminder labels the units of measurement for energy use per person as kg of oil equivalent per capita. This data set has 173 rows, with each row representing a different country, and 57 columns, with each column representing a different year.

Hypothesized Relationship

We are setting our explanatory variable to be GDP per capita, and our response variable as energy use per person. We believe that the relationship between GDP and energy use per Person will be positively correlated, meaning that a larger GDP for a country will be associated with more energy use per person. In addition, through the years, with a rise in accessibility of sustainable energy, we believe that the overall trend of energy use per person will be positive. Furthermore, the rise of globalization has increased GDPs over time, leading to another positive trend.

Data Cleaning Process and Decision-Making

Since each year in both of the data sets was its own separate column, making the data very difficult to analyze, we decided to pivot the data from wide to long format. This way, we could see each year as its own observation, rather than the difficult-to-read columns that they were in before. We also decided that in the GDP per capita data set, we wanted to get rid of any years that were not consistent with the years recorded in the energy use per person data set, so we made the decision to delete any data recorded before 1960, as well as anything after 2013. Additionally, the observations in the GDP per capita data set were not consistent. Some of the observations were number values, and some of them had abbreviations using character variables. For example, some of the observations said â4kâ to represent a GDP of $4,000, so in order to make the data consistent for the purpose of analyzing, we used a function to remove all instances of the letter âkâ and multiply the value by 1,000 to represent the âkâ numerically.

Linear Regression

GDP Per Capita Vs. Energy Use Per Person

We decided to use linear regression to model the relationship between GDP per capita and energy use per person. In our linear regression, we have defined GDP per capita as our explanatory variable, and energy use per person as our response variable.

Linear Regression Conditions

In order to apply a linear regression model to our data, we must make sure that our data satisfies the four conditions of linear regression. Our first condition, linearity, is met, in this case, because the relationship between the explanatory and response variable is proportional to one another. Our second condition, independence, is met because the result of GDP per capita each year is independent of one another for each recorded observation, and energy use per person each year is independent of one another for each recorded observation. Our third condition, normality, is met because for both GDP per capita and energy use per person have more than 30 observations, by the Central Limit Theorem. Lastly, our fourth condition of equal variance is met, because our residual plot shows no apparent pattern.

Visualization 2: Scatterplot

Because the relationship between GDP and energy use was similar over the years, we decided to average the data points over years for each country and create a scatter plot with average GDP in the x-axis and average energy use in the y-axis. We will be using this averaged data set moving on.

Code 
# Average values across the years

averaged_data <- final_data |>
  group_by(country) |>
  summarise(avg_energy = mean(energy_use),
            avg_gdp = mean(gdp))

averaged_data |>
  ggplot(aes(x=avg_gdp, 
             y=avg_energy)) +

Our linear regression model calculated by R reveals a strong, positive, and linear relationship between average GDP per capita and energy use per person, insinuating that, as GDP increases, energy use increases and that countries with a greater GDP may have a higher energy use per person. Visually, there are a couple unusual points. The point that is the highest up and to the right, at which average GDP per capita is just above 75000, and average energy use per person is about 15000, is quite far from the line of best fit. Another unusual point is the point at which average GDP per capita is about 35000, and average energy use is 10000.

Regression Model

Next, we will fit a linear regression model in order to derive the estimated regression equation.

Code 
# Carry out linear regression

energy_gdp_model <- lm(avg_energy ~ avg_gdp, 
                       data = averaged_data)

energy_gdp_model$coefficients
(Intercept)     avg_gdp 
 34.8143627   0.1214221
Code 
broom::tidy(energy_gdp_model)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 5
  term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
  <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
1 (Intercept)   34.8   194.          0.179 8.58e- 1
2 avg_gdp        0.121   0.00732    16.6   1.73e-31

From our regression model, we can come up with an linear equation to model the predicted values of energy use with GDP per capita inputs.

Equation: y = 0.121*x + 34.814

Put more simply, our linear regression model tells us that for every 1 unit increase in constant PPP dollars (GDP), the predicted energy use per person will increase by 0.121 kg of oil equivalent per capita (energy use). Our intercept tells us that a country with a GDP of 0 constant PPP dollars has energy use of 34.814 kg of oil equivalent per capita per person.

Model Fit

To test how well this linear regression model, we will look at the amount of variability that can be accounted for by our model.

Code 
# Display variances and calculate proportion of var

energy_gdp_model |>
  broom::augment() |>
  summarize(variance_energy = var(avg_energy),
            variance_fitted = var(.fitted),
            variance_residual = var(.resid)) |>
  mutate(prop = variance_fitted/variance_energy)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 4
  variance_energy variance_fitted variance_residual  prop
            <dbl>           <dbl>             <dbl> <dbl>
1        7191502.        5166040.          2025462. 0.718

Based on the proportion of variability that can be accounted for by our model, ~71.84% of the total variability can be attributed to our model, which is generally a good sign that our model fits well.

Simulation

Creating Simulated Data from Linear Model

Next, we will create simulated data from our linear model in order to compare how similar/different our observed data is from our simulated data as another measure of how well our linear model fits. To do this, we will generate predictions from our linear moedl and use those predictions to simulate observations.

Code 
# Set seed for consistent output

set.seed(1234)

# Create simulated data

simulated_data <- averaged_data |>
  
  # Remove NA values
  filter(!is.na(avg_energy)) |>
  
  # Mutate (add column) with predict to obtain predicted
  mutate(predicted = predict(energy_gdp_model)) |>
  mutate(simulated = predicted + rnorm(length(predicted), 
                                       mean = 0, 
                                       sd = sigma(energy_gdp_model))
         )

Generating Multiple Predictive Checks

To further analyze how well our regression model describes the relationship between GDP and energy use, we decided to generate 10,000 simulated datasets that we would expect to see if our regression model accurately described our relationship of interest. From there, we will then regress the observed data against each simulated data set and keep the R^2 value from each regression.

Code 
# Create function to accomplish one simulation

new_df <- averaged_data |>
  filter(!is.na(avg_energy))

sim_energy_data <- function(observed, lm){
  predicted <- predict({{lm}}) 
  simulated <- predicted + rnorm(length(predicted), 
                                       mean = 0, 
                                       sd = sigma({{lm}}))
  
  simulated_model <- lm({{observed}} ~ simulated)
  r_squared_val <- summary(simulated_model)$r.squared
  
  return(r_squared_val)
  
}

# Use map_df to do it 1000 times

r_squared_dist <- map_df(1:10000, 
                         ~tibble(r2 = sim_energy_data(observed = new_df$avg_energy, 
                                                      energy_gdp_model)))

To visualize the R^2 values, we will create a histogram of the R^2 values to see how well our model describes our relationship of interest.

Code 
# Plot to distribute R^2 values as histogram

ggplot(r_squared_dist,
       mapping = aes(
         x = r2
       )) +
  geom_histogram(
    aes(y = after_stat(count/sum(count))
        )
    ) +
  #geom_density(aes(y = after_stat(count/sum(count)))) +
  labs(
    x = "R-Squared value",
    y = "Proportion",
    title = "Distribution of R-Squared Values"
  ) +

The distribution of the R^2 values seems to be approximately normal and symmetric, centered around 0.52. This distribution suggests that the regression model of the simulated data against our observed data seems to have a moderately strong relationship.
